WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.270 --> 00:00:03.490
BRAD TEMPLETON: All right,
why don't we go ahead.

00:00:03.490 --> 00:00:03.860
Welcome.

00:00:03.860 --> 00:00:04.960
This is Authors at Google.

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:09.360
I'm Brad Templeton from Google
X. What we have today are two

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:11.770
of the most respected writers
of science fiction,

00:00:11.770 --> 00:00:13.670
particularly hard science
fiction, I think, we have in

00:00:13.670 --> 00:00:16.540
the field, Gregory Benford
and Larry Niven.

00:00:16.540 --> 00:00:19.960
Both of these men have been
nominated for, and won,

00:00:19.960 --> 00:00:22.090
science fiction's top awards,
the Hugo award

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:23.840
and the Nebula Award.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:27.550
You've probably read Larry's
books in what's called the

00:00:27.550 --> 00:00:31.200
Known Space series, including
works like "Ringworld" and

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:35.910
"Neutron Star." Gregory, I
think, got his first big hit

00:00:35.910 --> 00:00:38.890
with "Timescape," although I
know you had other things.

00:00:38.890 --> 00:00:41.760
But that won you the
Nebula Award.

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:44.920
Gregory's also a professor
of physics at UC Irvine.

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:49.970
And he is also now a biotech
entrepreneur, having worked to

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:52.930
found a company called
Genescient, whose goal is to

00:00:52.930 --> 00:00:55.010
stop human beings from
dying like flies.

00:00:55.010 --> 00:00:57.850
And he may be able to answer
some questions

00:00:57.850 --> 00:00:59.670
about that, as well.

00:00:59.670 --> 00:01:01.870
They have a new book that's just
come out this week called

00:01:01.870 --> 00:01:05.069
"Bowl of Heaven," that we see
on the screen, and they're

00:01:05.069 --> 00:01:05.900
going to talk about that.

00:01:05.900 --> 00:01:08.430
And there's many other things in
their careers that I'm sure

00:01:08.430 --> 00:01:09.390
will be interesting to us.

00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:19.690
And then we'll have Q&amp;A.

00:01:19.690 --> 00:01:21.040
GREGORY BENFORD: Thank you.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:22.540
LARRY NIVEN: Quite a crowd.

00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:23.175
GREGORY BENFORD: Nice crowd.

00:01:23.175 --> 00:01:25.520
See, and they're very orderly
and everything.

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:29.030
This is a talk mostly about--

00:01:29.030 --> 00:01:32.170
of course, what everybody in
the room probably knows--

00:01:32.170 --> 00:01:36.320
about the idea of what were
called Big Dumb Objects.

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:37.020
We'll get to that.

00:01:37.020 --> 00:01:40.460
But here's "Ringworld,"
Larry's.

00:01:40.460 --> 00:01:41.360
Remember "Ringworld"?

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:43.050
It's been 42 years.

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:43.700
LARRY NIVEN: It has been.

00:01:43.700 --> 00:01:48.470
We celebrated the 40th
anniversary by running a

00:01:48.470 --> 00:01:50.085
reprint and a lot
of publicity.

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:56.540
"Ringworld." Let me talk
about the Big Dumb--

00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:57.680
[FEEDBACK]

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:58.280
LARRY NIVEN: OK.

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:00.140
Trying that again.

00:02:00.140 --> 00:02:03.170
Let me talk about the Big
Dumb Object concept.

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:09.289
I like David Gerrold's phrase,
which was the Enormous Big

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:16.630
Thing, as the plot
line for a story.

00:02:16.630 --> 00:02:20.370
It sounds like nothing
happens.

00:02:20.370 --> 00:02:25.650
The key to nothing happening was
not our first discovery;

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:29.470
it was all the marvelous, empty
cities found by Conan

00:02:29.470 --> 00:02:31.775
the Cimmerian and Tarzan
of the Apes.

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:39.590
Empty cities can be explored
without things

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:41.860
happening all at once.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:43.570
You can discover what's
going on.

00:02:43.570 --> 00:02:45.260
You can find the interesting
things.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:47.250
You can get attacked
by the interesting

00:02:47.250 --> 00:02:50.120
monsters, one at a time.

00:02:50.120 --> 00:02:53.870
You drop Conan the Cimmerian
into New York City, he'll be

00:02:53.870 --> 00:02:56.570
bewildered for a long time.

00:02:56.570 --> 00:02:57.820
GREGORY BENFORD: Mostly
by the New Yorkers.

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:05.180
LARRY NIVEN: So I wrote
"Ringworld" as

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:07.780
nearly emptied of rulers.

00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:10.110
Nobody's running it.

00:03:10.110 --> 00:03:15.570
People came to be running it
in later volumes, but for

00:03:15.570 --> 00:03:18.920
"Ringworld," you don't even
see who built it.

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:23.650
It's just there, and
you can explore--

00:03:23.650 --> 00:03:26.910
well, with sky cycles
you can explore--

00:03:26.910 --> 00:03:30.820
about one quarter of the
distance across the width, is

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:32.710
how much got explored
in "Ringworld."

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:33.980
And that was my point.

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:35.760
It's just too big to look at.

00:03:39.030 --> 00:03:44.970
Notice, however, it's 93 million
miles in radius, 600

00:03:44.970 --> 00:03:46.830
million miles in
circumference.

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:50.370
It's the Earth's orbit,
approximately.

00:03:50.370 --> 00:03:54.910
And it's entirely filled
by a habitat.

00:03:54.910 --> 00:04:00.090
I made it a million miles
across, but that's arbitrary.

00:04:00.090 --> 00:04:04.330
You could make it two, or
half, whatever you like.

00:04:04.330 --> 00:04:08.410
It's so big that air leaking
over the rim walls, which

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:12.450
stand 1,000 miles high
at either edge--

00:04:12.450 --> 00:04:17.240
air leaking over the rim walls
doesn't rob you of your

00:04:17.240 --> 00:04:20.810
atmosphere in any decent time.

00:04:20.810 --> 00:04:24.780
It can last millions of
years doing that.

00:04:24.780 --> 00:04:26.460
GREGORY BENFORD:
Yeah, that's--

00:04:26.460 --> 00:04:26.890
LARRY NIVEN: Sorry.

00:04:26.890 --> 00:04:29.280
GREGORY BENFORD: And that's
what makes it dumb.

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:30.160
LARRY NIVEN: Yeah.

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:34.470
Well, it is perhaps
a dumb idea but it

00:04:34.470 --> 00:04:36.440
gives you better visuals.

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:37.620
And I was after the visuals.

00:04:37.620 --> 00:04:39.450
GREGORY BENFORD: It's dumb in
the sense of being struck dumb

00:04:39.450 --> 00:04:43.010
in awe at the prospect of even
exploring the thing.

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:45.290
You see, it's too big to cross,
but it's not too big to

00:04:45.290 --> 00:04:47.200
write about.

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:50.050
And the whole point--
next slide--

00:04:50.050 --> 00:04:55.610
is that this book, this whole
idea, descends also from

00:04:55.610 --> 00:04:59.490
something probably all of you
know, the Dyson Sphere idea.

00:04:59.490 --> 00:05:02.840
Because Freeman Dyson just said,
look, a really advanced

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:06.020
civilization will use all the
energy that's getting wasted

00:05:06.020 --> 00:05:08.580
into the night sky
by its star.

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:10.730
And it'll absorb it, and
use it for something.

00:05:10.730 --> 00:05:13.430
And then, of course because of
the laws of physics, it'll

00:05:13.430 --> 00:05:15.640
re-radiate it into
the infrared.

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:17.966
So the thing to look for, and
the reason this is published

00:05:17.966 --> 00:05:21.200
as a scientific paper, not
just as speculation, is

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:23.930
unexplained infrared objects
that are very compact

00:05:23.930 --> 00:05:25.180
in the night sky.

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:28.880
By the way, I'll get to a recent
grant given to look for

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:33.210
exactly that, in a little
bit, at UC Berkeley.

00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:37.000
LARRY NIVEN: The point of the
idea is that you can find it.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.590
You don't have to wait for
people who want to talk to us.

00:05:42.590 --> 00:05:45.560
Super-powered beings who have
been civilized for a billion

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:48.890
years are not likely to
want to talk to us.

00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:52.360
But if they've built Dyson
Spheres, you can find them.

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:54.010
GREGORY BENFORD: The galaxy
might easily be full of

00:05:54.010 --> 00:05:57.810
entities that don't really,
especially want to talk to us.

00:05:57.810 --> 00:05:59.080
For example, New Yorkers.

00:06:01.930 --> 00:06:06.440
So the whole idea comes also
from later ideas that people

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:07.420
have manifested.

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:10.220
Like, if it's in the stage of
being built, it's going to

00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:11.270
take awhile to build this.

00:06:11.270 --> 00:06:14.590
You could get a Dyson Swarm of
solar-powered satellites and

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:16.540
habitats like this.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:17.840
LARRY NIVEN: Next

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:18.720
GREGORY BENFORD: Or--

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:22.250
and you could put them in
various kinds of orbits that

00:06:22.250 --> 00:06:23.910
would make it look like,
what's called a Dyson

00:06:23.910 --> 00:06:25.690
Bubble, like this.

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:28.370
And there are all kinds of ideas
about how to maintain

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:31.220
these structures, and therefore,
over time, you

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:33.526
would use up the resource.

00:06:33.526 --> 00:06:36.010
LARRY NIVEN: Next.

00:06:36.010 --> 00:06:38.020
GREGORY BENFORD: And so, toward
the end it might even

00:06:38.020 --> 00:06:40.660
look like this.

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:44.250
And therefore, this is actually
an object we could

00:06:44.250 --> 00:06:47.470
look at using Kepler and another
satellites, and the

00:06:47.470 --> 00:06:51.550
recently finished infrared
search called WISE.

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:53.810
That's an acronym, as usual.

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:54.860
Next slide.

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:59.540
And therefore, a grant was just
gotten by Geoff Marcy

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:05.920
over at UC Berkeley that will
use the Lick Observatory,

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:10.130
right over there on the hills,
to look for Dyson Spheres,

00:07:10.130 --> 00:07:13.870
using the best data we now have
accumulated from those

00:07:13.870 --> 00:07:16.140
two missions, the WISE
and the Kepler.

00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:18.950
And you could actually, if you
care to, you could put this in

00:07:18.950 --> 00:07:20.830
as a public charity actually.

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:23.230
If you go to that address, you
can make a donation to the

00:07:23.230 --> 00:07:25.186
Dyson Sphere search.

00:07:25.186 --> 00:07:26.900
BRAD TEMPLETON: Why are you
looking at me, in particular?

00:07:26.900 --> 00:07:27.740
GREGORY BENFORD: Well,
because you're a

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:28.990
large infrared object.

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:32.847
Walked right into
that one, Brad.

00:07:35.470 --> 00:07:36.838
BRAD TEMPLETON: I'm a skilled
engineer, but my job is

00:07:36.838 --> 00:07:39.820
pushing a next button
on a slide.

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:42.230
GREGORY BENFORD: Exactly so.

00:07:42.230 --> 00:07:45.080
So you see, this is an
ongoing project.

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:46.950
I mean, I've known Geoff
