Next slide.

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:20.280
And of course, if you've been
around in this field long

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:22.680
enough, you know that there
were the ONeill fashion.

00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:25.940
The big fashion of the 1970's
was writing about these

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:29.080
cylinder colonies that we would
put in space and have

00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:30.790
habitats, and so forth.

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:33.260
Gerry O'Neill pursued this in
great detail, and showed that

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:33.920
you could do it.

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:36.490
And it was a good idea.

00:09:36.490 --> 00:09:39.490
And then, as typical in many--

00:09:39.490 --> 00:09:41.920
much of the evolution of science
fiction, it fades away

00:09:41.920 --> 00:09:43.310
and you get another idea.

00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:47.270
I can remember when I started
reading SF in the 1950's, the

00:09:47.270 --> 00:09:48.620
big idea was telepathy.

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:51.260
Whatever happened to
that idea, right?

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:52.550
Next.

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:54.270
LARRY NIVEN: Robert Silverberg
happened to that idea.

00:09:54.270 --> 00:09:55.620
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes, see,
Robert Silverberg.

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:58.420
Although Connie Willis is
writing a telepathy novel now,

00:09:58.420 --> 00:09:59.900
she told me.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:00.430
Next.

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:02.340
BRAD TEMPLETON: Pre-cognition
sort of failed too as a theme.

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:03.760
I wonder why they didn't
see that coming.

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:08.940
GREGORY BENFORD: That's good.

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:10.250
And then "Rendezvous
with Rama"--

00:10:10.250 --> 00:10:11.220
Arthur C. Clarke.

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:13.890
Big alien artifact, suspiciously
like an O'Neill

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:16.560
colony, comes into the solar
system, and takes off for

00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:17.580
parts unknown.

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:18.290
And you explore it.

00:10:18.290 --> 00:10:20.910
And again, there appears
to be nobody in charge.

00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:22.130
There's some aliens
crawling around.

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:24.480
They turned out to be
maintenance features.

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:25.970
Nobody knows what the
hell this was

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:27.720
for, and then it goes.

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:32.410
That's the thing is you try to
leave the wizard behind the

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:34.930
curtain, if you possibly can.

00:10:34.930 --> 00:10:36.180
Next.

00:10:38.700 --> 00:10:40.390
And this is ours.

00:10:40.390 --> 00:10:42.070
That's the Bowl of Heaven.

00:10:42.070 --> 00:10:46.150
That little bright point,
that's the star.

00:10:46.150 --> 00:10:50.620
The big blue and white zone is
the main habitable zone, but

00:10:50.620 --> 00:10:55.310
you actually could live under
that rather tan-colored

00:10:55.310 --> 00:10:58.290
section, which is mirrors.

00:10:58.290 --> 00:11:00.457
Not entirely mirrors,
but mostly.

00:11:00.457 --> 00:11:01.800
LARRY NIVEN: Notice
something here.

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:05.810
If you start with a Dyson
Sphere, and work within the

00:11:05.810 --> 00:11:09.680
laws of physics as we know them,
you're bound to wind up

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:14.060
using just the equator, and
spinning it for gravity.

00:11:14.060 --> 00:11:15.530
You spin it for gravity.

00:11:15.530 --> 00:11:18.870
The equator is the only thing
that will hold an atmosphere,

00:11:18.870 --> 00:11:21.210
because from the higher levels,

00:11:21.210 --> 00:11:23.420
atmosphere will flow down.

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:28.570
In this object, you still have
to pocket the atmosphere to

00:11:28.570 --> 00:11:30.130
avoid losing it.

00:11:30.130 --> 00:11:38.840
But the half-Dyson Sphere
doesn't quite work.

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:43.160
You wind up with a Ringworld
with a wok-shaped lid, and a

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:46.450
hole in the lid, if you're
going to make it move.

00:11:46.450 --> 00:11:48.530
GREGORY BENFORD: Tell
them the title.

00:11:48.530 --> 00:11:50.840
LARRY NIVEN: The title
is "Bowl of Heaven."

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:56.620
GREGORY BENFORD: But our first
title was "Wokworld." Somehow

00:11:56.620 --> 00:11:59.100
it didn't seem to quite--

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:01.290
LARRY NIVEN: And then I borrowed
a term, which I had

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:07.270
seen 48 years ago, for a cartoon
done for a set of

00:12:07.270 --> 00:12:09.830
cartoons done about
the Ringworld.

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:14.480
One of them laid out the plot
line in a few hundred words,

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:18.400
and called it "Cupworld." You've
got a half of a Dyson

00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:24.550
Sphere, space ports in the
handle, and night and day

00:12:24.550 --> 00:12:26.043
provided by orbiting tea bags.

00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:31.240
GREGORY BENFORD: And somehow
that didn't get written up.

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:32.260
I don't know why.

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:34.150
LARRY NIVEN: "Cupworld" wasn't
good enough. "Bowl of Heaven"

00:12:34.150 --> 00:12:35.890
works just fine.

00:12:35.890 --> 00:12:36.910
GREGORY BENFORD: And you'll
notice there are other

00:12:36.910 --> 00:12:39.710
features here.

00:12:39.710 --> 00:12:43.860
Those mirrors in a great
fraction of the bowl reflect

00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:47.430
back on to a tiny spot on the
surface of the rapidly

00:12:47.430 --> 00:12:48.660
rotating star.

00:12:48.660 --> 00:12:51.390
As you know, stellar
rotation gives you

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:52.680
strong magnetic fields.

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:55.140
It's true on our [? sun. ?]

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:57.150
Very high magnetic fields.

00:12:57.150 --> 00:13:02.570
And this concentrated energy
ignites a flare which turns

00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:03.490
into a jet.

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:06.340
It bulges out and then the
magnetic fields that are

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:13.230
entrained focus the jet so it
streams through the knothole.

00:13:13.230 --> 00:13:15.680
The whole system is
going somewhere.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:17.870
LARRY NIVEN: The star is
accelerating and the Bowl

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:20.060
follows because of
gravity, and some

00:13:20.060 --> 00:13:21.600
fancy magnetic fields.

00:13:21.600 --> 00:13:22.730
GREGORY BENFORD: Right.

00:13:22.730 --> 00:13:26.060
And here I was again able to
moonlight because I've

00:13:26.060 --> 00:13:28.770
published several dozen papers
on the dynamics, the

00:13:28.770 --> 00:13:32.300
stability, and origin of the
jets that come from the

00:13:32.300 --> 00:13:36.490
accretion disks around both
stars and black holes.

00:13:36.490 --> 00:13:40.250
And I published them in
"Astrophysical Journal," gone

00:13:40.250 --> 00:13:42.280
to a lot of conferences, and
then decided to use that

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:47.660
expertise, because jets form
naturally an astonishingly

00:13:47.660 --> 00:13:48.700
large number of times.

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:52.020
We now have seen hundreds of
jets coming from black hole

00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:54.630
regions around the universe.

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:58.070
And there are dozens around
black holes and

00:13:58.070 --> 00:14:01.430
stars in our galaxy.

00:14:01.430 --> 00:14:07.760
So the jet and the Bowl all make
an integrated system that

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:11.980
is a transport system that
people could live in.

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:14.160
Mysteries ensue.

00:14:14.160 --> 00:14:17.090
LARRY NIVEN: It's a Big Smart
Object because it needs

00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:19.160
constant maintenance.

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:21.610
You don't dare lose
your civilization.

00:14:21.610 --> 00:14:25.120
You lose your civilization,
you've lost your habitat.

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:28.940
It'll spin out of control, it'll
impact the sun, it'll go

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:30.210
straight to hell.

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:31.050
GREGORY BENFORD: Right.

00:14:31.050 --> 00:14:36.300
Yet much of the land in the
Bowl of Heaven is natural.

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:37.270
It's a natural habitat.

00:14:37.270 --> 00:14:38.510
It has enormous parks.

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:39.560
They utterly dominate.

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:42.020
It's not just a big
New York City.

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:46.320
And so you have to wonder, why
was this built, who built it,

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:48.020
and what's its point?

00:14:48.020 --> 00:14:50.470
And obviously the point is that
it's going somewhere,

00:14:50.470 --> 00:14:53.500
unlike "Ringworld."

00:14:53.500 --> 00:14:55.120
Interesting plot point, right?

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:57.050
All of this is the pre-thinking
before you write

00:14:57.050 --> 00:14:58.310
the first line.

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:01.940
And in the first line someone is
waking up-- a human, a guy,

00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:03.100
a biologist--

00:15:03.100 --> 00:15:07.350
on a starship that's headed
for a planet called Glory,

00:15:07.350 --> 00:15:09.670
because the watch officers--

00:15:09.670 --> 00:15:13.000
almost all the expedition
is in the deep

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:17.070
sleep, and fairly cold--

00:15:17.070 --> 00:15:20.320
the watch officers suddenly saw
appear off to the side,

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:23.150
this thing, because they
had overtaken it.

00:15:23.150 --> 00:15:24.710
Because you couldn't
see it from behind.

00:15:24.710 --> 00:15:26.080
The star was blocked.

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:29.170
And the jet wasn't quite
luminous enough to register at

00:15:29.170 --> 00:15:29.890
a distance.

00:15:29.890 --> 00:15:31.340
And the thing is about
a quarter of a

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:34.520
light year away anyway.

00:15:34.520 --> 00:15:36.490
LARRY NIVEN: What Greg hasn't
said is, this thing is

00:15:36.490 --> 00:15:39.530
accelerating directly away
from Earth, with the same

00:15:39.530 --> 00:15:43.410
target as the spaceship that
contains our protagonists.

00:15:43.410 --> 00:15:45.860
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes.

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:49.660
LARRY NIVEN: They were
bound to catch up.

00:15:49.660 --> 00:15:53.080
The Bowl wasn't big enough to
see until they got closer.

00:15:53.080 --> 00:15:58.820
And of course they're moving
through the flare.

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:00.090
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah.

00:16:00.090 --> 00:16:02.950
Which has some implications
about what's been happening to

00:16:02.950 --> 00:16:06.670
the starship, which we'll let
you discover when you read the

00:16:06.670 --> 00:16:07.920
Google discounted book.

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:12.960
So all of this is the beginning
of the plot.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:14.960
Notice how much thinking you've
got to do before you

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:16.730
can write the first page.

00:16:16.730 --> 00:16:19.440
It really does help to plan.

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:21.970
LARRY NIVEN: Until you write
the first page, it's all

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:23.860
recreation.

00:16:23.860 --> 00:16:27.710
Collaborations don't become work
until you start writing.

00:16:27.710 --> 00:16:29.030
Until then it's just fun.

00:16:29.030 --> 00:16:29.350
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah.

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:34.080
Until then it's an excuse
to meet in a bar.

00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:37.010
LARRY NIVEN: I have spent a
whole afternoon walking with a

00:16:37.010 --> 00:16:43.050
guy named Michael [? Crew ?],
carving out a novel as we

00:16:43.050 --> 00:16:45.220
walked around the hills
of Berkeley.

00:16:45.220 --> 00:16:48.710
We get back to the house, and we
find out that neither of us

00:16:48.710 --> 00:16:49.960
actually wants to write.

00:16:52.410 --> 00:16:54.330
GREGORY BENFORD: You suck
all the fun out of it.

00:16:54.330 --> 00:16:55.690
That's the thing.

00:16:55.690 --> 00:16:57.070
Don't eat the cream first.

00:16:57.070 --> 00:16:59.800
That's the usual rule
about desserts.

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:01.050
Yes.

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:06.730
The Bowl spins quite rapidly, as
you would guess, to create

00:17:06.730 --> 00:17:08.170
an artificial gravity.

00:17:08.170 --> 00:17:10.829
And as you'll see, in your
location the Bowl--

00:17:10.829 --> 00:17:12.790
and all the bowl has
habitat in it.

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:17.750
It's not just mirrors plus a
habitat somewhere else--

00:17:17.750 --> 00:17:19.619
you can have very
light gravity.

00:17:19.619 --> 00:17:21.500
And therefore the species
are different.

00:17:21.500 --> 00:17:23.380
The living conditions
are different.

00:17:23.380 --> 00:17:26.210
And the humans in this novel get
to experience several of

00:17:26.210 --> 00:17:28.540
these different g's.

00:17:28.540 --> 00:17:33.860
The main equatorial section is
called the Great Plain, and

00:17:33.860 --> 00:17:36.740
it's at 0.8g.

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:38.400
This sketch is in the book.

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:39.890
Use your own work.

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:43.860
LARRY NIVEN: The sketches, the
visuals, all of the visual

00:17:43.860 --> 00:17:49.140
were done from sketches
we made by Don Davis.

00:17:49.140 --> 00:17:52.690
We took a flat fee for doing
several paintings.

00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:53.580
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:54.810
Next.

00:17:54.810 --> 00:17:58.160
Several paintings indeed,
because this is a close up of

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:00.100
the Don Davis.

00:18:00.100 --> 00:18:03.360
He's a guy I've known since
Chesley Bonestell introduced

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:06.680
him to me, and Don
was 18 years old,

00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:09.620
back in the late 1960's.

00:18:09.620 --> 00:18:10.300
Here's a close up.

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:11.460
You can see the mirror zone.

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:18.330
And you can see the storms above
both oceans and land in

00:18:18.330 --> 00:18:19.640
the Great Plain.

00:18:19.640 --> 00:18:23.210
And you'll see everything at
such a scale, you can't tell

00:18:23.210 --> 00:18:26.070
anything about the inhabitants
at this range.

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:28.350
Which is largely true of the
Earth, except for some large

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:30.190
constructions.

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:31.440
Next.

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:35.630
So the--

00:18:38.760 --> 00:18:42.510
LARRY NIVEN: In fact the thing
looks so planet-like that you

00:18:42.510 --> 00:18:46.080
have to keep remembering, and
the protagonists have to keep

00:18:46.080 --> 00:18:51.450
remembering, you're looking
across interplanetary scales,

00:18:51.450 --> 00:18:55.020
objects as far away as Mars.

00:18:55.020 --> 00:18:59.110
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah but you
can tell essentially the major

00:18:59.110 --> 00:19:02.970
characteristics over an
interplanetary distance.

00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:06.380
And so this is a scene that
occurs fairly early in.

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:11.820
The way for this starship to
actually maneuver in is, first

00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:15.020
it has to lose some velocity,
and it wants to explore the

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:18.950
object, so it flies up the
jet, to decelerate.

00:19:18.950 --> 00:19:20.500
Great scene to write.

00:19:20.500 --> 00:19:23.300
And this is a Don
Davis painting.

00:19:23.300 --> 00:19:24.890
You'll see the larger
version in

00:19:24.890 --> 00:19:26.270
unfortunately black and white.

00:19:26.270 --> 00:19:28.220
Although in the e-Edition
maybe it's in color.

00:19:28.220 --> 00:19:31.860
I actually haven't even looked
at the e-Edition.

00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:38.460
And notice the large magnetic
coils around

00:19:38.460 --> 00:19:40.240
the rim of the knothole.

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:41.950
And there's some other magnetic
features too.

00:19:41.950 --> 00:19:44.910
There's a lot of magnetism in
this, because I've done a lot

00:19:44.910 --> 00:19:48.280
of classical electrodynamics,
and I taught it at UC Irvine--

00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:49.725
the advanced class.

00:19:49.725 --> 00:19:52.740
They've got a graduate class.

00:19:52.740 --> 00:19:54.990
To me the most important
technology of the last 200

00:19:54.990 --> 00:19:56.940
years has clearly been
that that derives

00:19:56.940 --> 00:19:58.540
from the Maxwell Equations.

00:19:58.540 --> 00:20:00.690
I mean, it's made this
company, right?

00:20:00.690 --> 00:20:03.700
I mean it's the key
technology.

00:20:03.700 --> 00:20:06.160
And we're still mining it.

00:20:06.160 --> 00:20:09.000
Only a few months ago, some guys
at Imperial College in

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:13.080
London announced an easy way
to produce a coherent

00:20:13.080 --> 00:20:17.040
microwave emitter from a solid
by flashing light on it.

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:18.330
Completely a new discovery.

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:22.440
It's going to revolutionize
microwave transmission.

00:20:22.440 --> 00:20:25.040
It's amazing where you don't
even have to tune.

00:20:27.910 --> 00:20:29.270
LARRY NIVEN: And it gets
us cheap [? sugary ?]

00:20:29.270 --> 00:20:29.840
[? cereals. ?]

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:31.420
GREGORY BENFORD: That's right.

00:20:31.420 --> 00:20:34.470
Yeah that's an immediate
application.

00:20:34.470 --> 00:20:38.770
Here's a view from standing in
the Great Plain, looking out

00:20:38.770 --> 00:20:41.060
into the distance on
a very clear day.

00:20:41.060 --> 00:20:42.810
This is a clear day.

00:20:42.810 --> 00:20:44.990
It has a deep ocean, which
is held in by a

00:20:44.990 --> 00:20:47.510
membrane at the top.

00:20:47.510 --> 00:20:50.650
And this is the kind of view
that we imagine would be true

00:20:50.650 --> 00:20:54.840
if you were able to stand there
and look across at and

00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:56.190
see such great distances.

00:20:56.190 --> 00:20:58.070
This is on a clear
day, remember.

00:20:58.070 --> 00:21:02.100
So you see some fading with
distance but not a lot.

00:21:02.100 --> 00:21:03.350
Next.

00:21:05.950 --> 00:21:08.090
And here's another part
of that view.

00:21:08.090 --> 00:21:09.790
It's all part of one painting.

00:21:09.790 --> 00:21:11.190
You'll notice in the foreground
there's what we

00:21:11.190 --> 00:21:14.120
call a zig-zag tree, which is
an adaptation we haven't

00:21:14.120 --> 00:21:17.800
explained yet to this world.

00:21:17.800 --> 00:21:21.220
There's a human walking
over toward the left.

00:21:21.220 --> 00:21:24.730
And you can see the scale, as
the whole thing just runs away

00:21:24.730 --> 00:21:27.480
into the distance, over
colossal distances.

00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:32.150
It's inverse to a planet, in
that the horizon tilts up, so

00:21:32.150 --> 00:21:35.300
you can see great distances.

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:36.730
But there's something
else in there.

00:21:36.730 --> 00:21:38.470
Next slide.

00:21:38.470 --> 00:21:41.790
Something else within
view, and it's this.

00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:43.410
This is an animal.

00:21:43.410 --> 00:21:45.260
It looks like a fish because
it flies through

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:47.050
the air, very slowly.

00:21:47.050 --> 00:21:48.300
It's like a giant blimp.

00:21:50.580 --> 00:21:53.740
And it's actually the
means of transport--

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:56.890
one of the means of transport
that the inhabitants use.

00:21:56.890 --> 00:21:59.930
Because, guess what, there's
not going to be a climate

00:21:59.930 --> 00:22:03.720
change problem here because
there are no fossil fuels.

00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:06.240
You have to get around
in some other means.

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:09.720
You could make fuels
of course, the

00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:11.460
way we do with ethanol.

00:22:11.460 --> 00:22:15.750
But it's cheaper to get around,
since you've got a lot

00:22:15.750 --> 00:22:19.980
of time, in a method that
doesn't burn something.

00:22:19.980 --> 00:22:22.270
Because you have to be careful
of the environment.

00:22:22.270 --> 00:22:23.810
You don't want too
much oxidation

00:22:23.810 --> 00:22:25.850
to run out of control.

00:22:25.850 --> 00:22:28.420
So that's some of the
environment that we have spent

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:31.640
a whole lot of time and
fun in designing.

00:22:31.640 --> 00:22:33.860
The whole strategy of the first
book is to show you a

00:22:33.860 --> 00:22:37.200
lot of things, let you reach
some assumptions, and then

00:22:37.200 --> 00:22:41.920
undermine them and prove them
false in the second book.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:46.180
That's what makes
it fun for us.

00:22:46.180 --> 00:22:49.700
So anything more about--
this is called a sky

00:22:49.700 --> 00:22:50.520
fish, by the way.

00:22:50.520 --> 00:22:54.120
It's called by the humans
a sky fish.

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:55.200
LARRY NIVEN: You can't
pronounce the

00:22:55.200 --> 00:22:56.810
word in Bird Folk.

00:22:59.430 --> 00:23:02.240
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah because
the Bird Folk are the people

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:05.770
who run this place, and they
have a lot of feathers.

00:23:05.770 --> 00:23:08.260
And it's one of their major
modes of expression.

00:23:08.260 --> 00:23:11.620
And they regard these curious
primates, who come on-board

00:23:11.620 --> 00:23:12.560
and have to be, of course,

00:23:12.560 --> 00:23:14.460
immediately grabbed and corralled.

00:23:14.460 --> 00:23:17.680
I mean, you don't want new
influences, right?

00:23:17.680 --> 00:23:21.390
You don't want instability in
the Bowl, because instability

00:23:21.390 --> 00:23:23.320
means death.

00:23:23.320 --> 00:23:25.710
But these primates have this
curious thing that--

00:23:25.710 --> 00:23:27.820
I mean they make gestures
with their arms.

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:29.690
They have these funny little
facial expressions, and they

00:23:29.690 --> 00:23:31.450
try to convey meaning
with them.

00:23:31.450 --> 00:23:34.480
But they don't use the full
glory of a fan feather

00:23:34.480 --> 00:23:35.240
presentation.

00:23:35.240 --> 00:23:36.930
They can't change colors.

00:23:36.930 --> 00:23:39.150
They can't rattle, and
rustle, and move.

00:23:39.150 --> 00:23:42.970
I mean it just shows you
how limited they are.

00:23:42.970 --> 00:23:43.750
Poor things.

00:23:43.750 --> 00:23:46.000
And they have this kind
of simple starship.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.960
Well we've seen a lot
of those before.

00:23:48.960 --> 00:23:50.810
They come and go, you know.

00:23:50.810 --> 00:23:52.580
It's a different attitude.

00:23:52.580 --> 00:23:53.730
LARRY NIVEN: We've been
avoiding some

00:23:53.730 --> 00:23:55.670
spoilers, so far.

00:23:55.670 --> 00:23:57.400
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes and we're
going to keep avoiding

00:23:57.400 --> 00:24:00.860
them, aren't we?

00:24:00.860 --> 00:24:02.270
LARRY NIVEN: That was
topic I was--

00:24:02.270 --> 00:24:04.850
I'm not going to tell them about
the Builders, right?

00:24:04.850 --> 00:24:06.560
GREGORY BENFORD: Oh, right

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:10.140
LARRY NIVEN: As with
"Ringworld," you don't know

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:14.775
much about the Builders until
you get into the book.

00:24:14.775 --> 00:24:15.770
GREGORY BENFORD: Right.

00:24:15.770 --> 00:24:18.640
Because it's just too damn much
to show you all of New

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:19.920
York in one day, right?

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:22.750
LARRY NIVEN: But the Builders
do go onstage quick.

00:24:22.750 --> 00:24:26.690
They have to with a Big Smart
Object because that's who is

00:24:26.690 --> 00:24:27.820
running everything.

00:24:27.820 --> 00:24:31.964
Their quite obvious,
quite obtrusive.

00:24:31.964 --> 00:24:32.960
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes.

00:24:32.960 --> 00:24:34.530
But there's an old saying--
my father was a

00:24:34.530 --> 00:24:35.830
professional army officer.

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:38.080
That's how I ended up spending
three years in occupied

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:40.840
Germany, three years
in occupied Japan.

00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:43.310
And I learned things about
hierarchies, both in Japan and

00:24:43.310 --> 00:24:44.200
in the army.

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:49.600
When you go into the GQ, the
General Headquarters, the

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:54.400
first person you meet
is not a general.

00:24:54.400 --> 00:24:57.890
That rule applies to the Bowl.

