Conservative means careful
because Big Smart Objects

00:25:05.050 --> 00:25:11.080
means it's not mutually stable
like the Ringworld was

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:12.490
supposedly first
thought to be.

00:25:12.490 --> 00:25:14.190
It turns out it's not
usually stable.

00:25:14.190 --> 00:25:16.940
In fact I gave the problem of,
calculate the stability of the

00:25:16.940 --> 00:25:22.030
Ringworld as a problem on the
qualifying exam for the PhD at

00:25:22.030 --> 00:25:23.520
UC Irvine, one year.

00:25:23.520 --> 00:25:28.060
And guess how many people out of
18 candidates managed to do

00:25:28.060 --> 00:25:31.780
the calculation correctly, and
reach the right conclusion.

00:25:31.780 --> 00:25:32.570
One?

00:25:32.570 --> 00:25:34.660
Do I hear two?

00:25:34.660 --> 00:25:36.580
Zero?

00:25:36.580 --> 00:25:37.490
How many pessimists--

00:25:37.490 --> 00:25:40.290
how many vote for zero?

00:25:40.290 --> 00:25:42.310
Yeah, well you're right
to be skeptical.

00:25:42.310 --> 00:25:45.960
The correct number is
two, out of 18.

00:25:45.960 --> 00:25:47.650
They said it was one of the
toughest problems they had

00:25:47.650 --> 00:25:49.430
ever had on an exam,
because they hadn't

00:25:49.430 --> 00:25:50.790
seen one like it before.

00:25:50.790 --> 00:25:54.060
And you see, I wanted to
privilege the people who had

00:25:54.060 --> 00:25:59.900
read "Ringworld." I've never
said that in public before.

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:02.545
It was 1977, so they
had a chance.

00:26:05.700 --> 00:26:07.270
OK.

00:26:07.270 --> 00:26:08.150
BRAD TEMPLETON: Really, because
we did that one in

00:26:08.150 --> 00:26:09.730
high school integration.

00:26:09.730 --> 00:26:11.680
I mean just, no mass,
no gravity

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:13.580
inside a disc or a sphere.

00:26:13.580 --> 00:26:14.030
We did that.

00:26:14.030 --> 00:26:14.480
But anyway.

00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:14.990
GREGORY BENFORD: That's right.

00:26:14.990 --> 00:26:16.600
Yeah I mean you can do it.

00:26:16.600 --> 00:26:17.610
It's just an interval.

00:26:17.610 --> 00:26:22.470
LARRY NIVEN: They were using
"Ringworld" calculations at my

00:26:22.470 --> 00:26:25.730
high school last
time I visited.

00:26:25.730 --> 00:26:28.040
GREGORY BENFORD: You can
calculate the potential field,

00:26:28.040 --> 00:26:31.230
and then show that the lateral
movement increases the energy,

00:26:31.230 --> 00:26:32.580
and therefore the system
will go that way.

00:26:32.580 --> 00:26:35.440
So that Ringworld will simply
slide into the star.

00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:38.860
If you push it will
just keep going.

00:26:38.860 --> 00:26:41.100
Like a ball rolling
down a hill.

00:26:41.100 --> 00:26:43.240
LARRY NIVEN: Which is why there
are attitude jets in the

00:26:43.240 --> 00:26:44.060
second book.

00:26:44.060 --> 00:26:46.510
GREGORY BENFORD: Right.

00:26:46.510 --> 00:26:49.270
And so in "Bowl of Heaven"--

00:26:49.270 --> 00:26:52.010
actually, I think I left
this out deliberately.

00:26:52.010 --> 00:26:54.320
It'll be in the second book--
somebody says, how come they

00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:57.760
just don't turn off
the jet and coast?

00:26:57.760 --> 00:26:59.010
Think for a minute.

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:03.870
LARRY NIVEN: Bowl.

00:27:03.870 --> 00:27:05.120
Interstellar wind.

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:09.070
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah.

00:27:09.070 --> 00:27:11.160
And the star.

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:12.070
Who wins?

00:27:12.070 --> 00:27:14.160
It's a complicated
dynamics problem.

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:15.080
LARRY NIVEN: Yeah.

00:27:15.080 --> 00:27:17.490
The wind stops the Bowl.

00:27:17.490 --> 00:27:20.790
The sun, being more massive
keeps going.

00:27:20.790 --> 00:27:21.950
You lose your sun.

00:27:21.950 --> 00:27:22.830
Now what?

00:27:22.830 --> 00:27:23.620
GREGORY BENFORD: Right.

00:27:23.620 --> 00:27:29.200
But it could be, if you're in a
low density region that the

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:30.560
sun's gravity wins.

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:33.330
And either way it goes,
it's unstable.

00:27:33.330 --> 00:27:36.260
If you turn off the
jet you're dead.

00:27:36.260 --> 00:27:38.630
The Bowl is spinning, that keeps
your orientation, but it

00:27:38.630 --> 00:27:41.030
doesn't help you with
the instability.

00:27:41.030 --> 00:27:42.660
And there are other
problems too.

00:27:42.660 --> 00:27:43.940
How is this maintained?

00:27:43.940 --> 00:27:46.470
By a complicated set of magnetic
fields, a rapidly

00:27:46.470 --> 00:27:50.640
spinning object with electrical
charge, generates a

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:52.740
magnetic field.

00:27:52.740 --> 00:27:56.110
And lots of great engineering,
which I hope will form the

00:27:56.110 --> 00:28:00.890
basis for future qualifying
exam questions.

00:28:00.890 --> 00:28:03.010
Well you've probably
read this one.

00:28:03.010 --> 00:28:03.870
Is this the last?

00:28:03.870 --> 00:28:05.700
No it's not.

00:28:05.700 --> 00:28:06.210
Yeah.

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:08.890
So smart means vigilant.

00:28:08.890 --> 00:28:09.600
You can read that.

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:10.850
It's more effective.

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:21.910
LARRY NIVEN: I didn't deal with
the problem of drilling

00:28:21.910 --> 00:28:26.660
in the vacuum on the Ringworld,
long ago.

00:28:26.660 --> 00:28:29.030
It's the reason you don't
find oil wells.

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:36.540
GREGORY BENFORD: But if you're
on the Bowl, and you drill

00:28:36.540 --> 00:28:39.140
through, you're not only going
to be sucked through by the

00:28:39.140 --> 00:28:43.220
vacuum, you have a velocity
relative to the rest of the

00:28:43.220 --> 00:28:46.220
background of a hundreds
of kilometers a second.

00:28:46.220 --> 00:28:48.550
And it's going to get you
into trouble because the

00:28:48.550 --> 00:28:49.930
outside of the Bowl--

00:28:49.930 --> 00:28:51.760
we have some interesting things
about this in the

00:28:51.760 --> 00:28:52.800
second book--

00:28:52.800 --> 00:28:55.240
the outside the Bowl is
not just bare skin.

00:28:55.240 --> 00:28:56.580
It has constructs on it.

00:28:56.580 --> 00:28:58.220
It's useful.

00:28:58.220 --> 00:29:01.200
So you're almost certainly going
to run into something.

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:06.240
So it's going to be a very
bad idea to think about.

00:29:06.240 --> 00:29:09.600
And they have safeguards
against that.

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:13.980
The point about this is to say,
why should we think about

00:29:13.980 --> 00:29:15.000
this enormous object?

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:18.050
Well it's a way of thinking
about, what would intelligent

00:29:18.050 --> 00:29:22.490
life do, if it really had a lot
of time, and a big energy

00:29:22.490 --> 00:29:27.840
budget, and had motivations
that are not ours.

00:29:27.840 --> 00:29:30.710
There's an old story told about
bringing an aboriginal

00:29:30.710 --> 00:29:33.740
from Australia in the 19th
century to London.

00:29:33.740 --> 00:29:36.070
And he looked at St. Paul's
Cathedral, and these

00:29:36.070 --> 00:29:39.130
buildings, and these streets,
and he said, you know, this is

00:29:39.130 --> 00:29:42.090
very impressive, but
why did you do it?

00:29:42.090 --> 00:29:43.420
Why did you bother?

00:29:43.420 --> 00:29:46.310
I mean, he couldn't see the
point of building large

00:29:46.310 --> 00:29:47.850
buildings and a city.

00:29:47.850 --> 00:29:51.140
It just didn't seem like
something he wanted to do.

00:29:51.140 --> 00:29:55.040
Well maybe the Bowl of Heaven
will be something that we

00:29:55.040 --> 00:29:56.720
wouldn't want to do,
but somebody did.

00:29:56.720 --> 00:29:57.670
And who was that?

00:29:57.670 --> 00:30:00.820
That's really the thrust
of the book.

00:30:00.820 --> 00:30:03.692
And, oh by the way, why is it
going to Glory, the target for

00:30:03.692 --> 00:30:05.630
the starship.

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:07.450
And then some other things.

00:30:07.450 --> 00:30:09.810
As we always say toward
end, events ensue.

00:30:12.920 --> 00:30:14.610
This is why it's fun to
write these books.

00:30:14.610 --> 00:30:18.360
It's because it's just kind of
fun to fool around with ideas.

00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:20.280
And from the point of view of
the guy whose published over

00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:25.590
200 scientific papers, it is
very much like doing science,

00:30:25.590 --> 00:30:27.240
when it's really good.

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:29.010
That is, you're having
new ideas.

00:30:29.010 --> 00:30:30.950
You're working them out
in a rigorous way.

00:30:30.950 --> 00:30:33.980
The writing, as Larry said,
is the hard part.

00:30:33.980 --> 00:30:35.570
LARRY NIVEN: And things
keep surprising you.

00:30:35.570 --> 00:30:36.220
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes.

00:30:36.220 --> 00:30:36.730
That's right.

00:30:36.730 --> 00:30:39.480
And so we keeping kicking
my ideas back and forth.

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:42.320
LARRY NIVEN: We've been hard at
work on the second book as

00:30:42.320 --> 00:30:47.600
we drove around the Southern
California area.

00:30:47.600 --> 00:30:51.240
If you can carpool, you
can collaborate.

00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:53.970
Yeah and it's more productive
than just

00:30:53.970 --> 00:30:56.900
listening to classic rock.

00:30:56.900 --> 00:30:58.620
So it's a fun process.

00:30:58.620 --> 00:31:03.760
And our intention is to finish
this subject in two books.

00:31:03.760 --> 00:31:06.500
Now "Ringworld" has how
many books now?

00:31:06.500 --> 00:31:07.710
LARRY NIVEN: "Ringworld"
is four, and

00:31:07.710 --> 00:31:10.090
"Ringworld" is finished.

00:31:10.090 --> 00:31:11.410
It was going to be one.

00:31:11.410 --> 00:31:12.570
GREGORY BENFORD: Until
further notice, then.

00:31:12.570 --> 00:31:14.410
LARRY NIVEN: This one, we
planned two, and we're still

00:31:14.410 --> 00:31:15.350
planning two.

00:31:15.350 --> 00:31:18.180
It's not going to be one of
those seven-part trilogies.

00:31:18.180 --> 00:31:20.810
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes.

00:31:20.810 --> 00:31:23.350
Or even a three-part trilogy
because trilogies--

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:24.940
the classic problem with
trilogies is the

00:31:24.940 --> 00:31:26.180
middle book, right?

00:31:26.180 --> 00:31:28.270
How to eliminate this problem,
make it two books.

00:31:31.510 --> 00:31:33.040
Seems simple.

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:35.130
So, why don't we do Q&amp;A?

00:31:35.130 --> 00:31:40.550
But it actually announces part
of the narrative strategy of

00:31:40.550 --> 00:31:41.390
telling such stories.

00:31:41.390 --> 00:31:43.410
So we thought what's
the opposite?

00:31:43.410 --> 00:31:44.850
LARRY NIVEN: It's
a critic's term.

00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:49.880
It's a critics who was not
impressed by a flood of Big

00:31:49.880 --> 00:31:53.140
Dumb Object stories.

00:31:53.140 --> 00:32:00.210
"Ringworld" followed by
"Orbitsville," and the

00:32:00.210 --> 00:32:02.670
"Rendezvous with Rama,"
and several others.

00:32:02.670 --> 00:32:04.410
GREGORY BENFORD: And
Farley's books--

00:32:04.410 --> 00:32:08.590
He wrote a Big Dumb Object
trilogy, which is the only

00:32:08.590 --> 00:32:13.220
part of his work which is out
of print, he told me.

00:32:13.220 --> 00:32:15.120
LARRY NIVEN: Well, he broke
too many physics

00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:16.050
laws with that one.

00:32:16.050 --> 00:32:16.800
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah,
that's true.

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:19.550
LARRY NIVEN: And bent
probability a lot too far.

00:32:19.550 --> 00:32:21.140
BRAD TEMPLETON: Wait a minute,
are you talking about "Titan?"

00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:21.690
LARRY NIVEN: Yes.

00:32:21.690 --> 00:32:22.880
BRAD TEMPLETON: That
wasn't dumb.

00:32:22.880 --> 00:32:24.070
LARRY NIVEN: Wasn't it?

00:32:24.070 --> 00:32:24.770
No, you're right.

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:26.270
Someone was in charge.

00:32:26.270 --> 00:32:28.970
GREGORY BENFORD: Oh there was
somebody charge, yes.

00:32:28.970 --> 00:32:30.320
That's true.

00:32:30.320 --> 00:32:34.980
But it tended, like most ideas
in science fiction, to have a

00:32:34.980 --> 00:32:39.610
half-life of roughly a decade,
and then to go away.

00:32:39.610 --> 00:32:42.270
So now it's back.

00:32:42.270 --> 00:32:42.480
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:43.050
Thanks for coming.

00:32:43.050 --> 00:32:44.990
It's great fun to
have you here.

00:32:44.990 --> 00:32:46.660
How are the inhabitants
protected

00:32:46.660 --> 00:32:49.750
against ionizing radiation?

00:32:49.750 --> 00:32:51.820
LARRY NIVEN: Lots of atmosphere,
for one thing.

00:32:51.820 --> 00:32:56.270
And for another, that sun is a
wretched little red dwarf.

00:32:56.270 --> 00:32:56.820
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah.

00:32:56.820 --> 00:32:58.440
LARRY NIVEN: You've got the
flare, but it's generating

00:32:58.440 --> 00:33:00.250
mostly heat.

00:33:00.250 --> 00:33:03.160
Check me out on this, because
you're the expert.

00:33:03.160 --> 00:33:04.810
GREGORY BENFORD: That's
true. , No, I mean,

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:06.060
about what you said.

00:33:08.810 --> 00:33:09.640
LARRY NIVEN: OK.

00:33:09.640 --> 00:33:11.550
GREGORY BENFORD: But it's
also the magnetic field.

00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:14.780
LARRY NIVEN: Hundreds of
kilometers of atmosphere being

00:33:14.780 --> 00:33:22.240
held in by what is essentially
the far future descendants of

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:23.530
a sandwich baggie.

00:33:23.530 --> 00:33:24.960
GREGORY BENFORD: Yes.

00:33:24.960 --> 00:33:25.460
Right.

00:33:25.460 --> 00:33:30.250
But the whole region is
magnetically dominated, and so

00:33:30.250 --> 00:33:32.760
you fend off an lot
of cosmic rays.

00:33:32.760 --> 00:33:33.830
LARRY NIVEN: Flare
is confined.

00:33:33.830 --> 00:33:36.990
If you fiddle with the flare,
you're going to get ionizing

00:33:36.990 --> 00:33:38.790
radiation where you
don't want it.

00:33:38.790 --> 00:33:40.080
Something to remember.

00:33:40.080 --> 00:33:41.190
GREGORY BENFORD: That's right.

00:33:41.190 --> 00:33:43.470
The trick in the system is that

00:33:43.470 --> 00:33:45.920
the jet is very dangerous.

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:48.670
And it will always
work perfectly,

00:33:48.670 --> 00:33:50.020
until the second book.

00:33:52.750 --> 00:33:57.780
AUDIENCE: So you said the Bowl's
going somewhere, and

00:33:57.780 --> 00:33:58.690
you said it's hard to stop.

00:33:58.690 --> 00:33:59.940
LARRY NIVEN: The Bowl is a
spacecraft and it's been

00:33:59.940 --> 00:34:01.840
traveling for a long time.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:05.100
It's visited many,
many places.

00:34:05.100 --> 00:34:06.920
AUDIENCE: Well, anyway, you said
it would be very hard to

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:10.870
stop, or I assume, even turn,
and get into an orbit.

00:34:10.870 --> 00:34:13.530
So what the heck's going
to happen about that?

00:34:13.530 --> 00:34:13.760
LARRY NIVEN: There's lots
of space out there.

00:34:13.760 --> 00:34:15.139
Light years are big.

00:34:15.139 --> 00:34:16.080
Light years are big.

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:19.140
You don't need to make
a hairpin turn.

00:34:19.140 --> 00:34:21.150
And if you did, you could
do it around the sun.

00:34:21.150 --> 00:34:24.310
AUDIENCE: But even an
infinitesimal turn would, I

00:34:24.310 --> 00:34:26.380
assume, give you the same
problems you described with

00:34:26.380 --> 00:34:28.429
turning off the jet.

00:34:28.429 --> 00:34:29.900
GREGORY BENFORD: Well, remember
you could apply

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:31.469
torque over a very long time.

00:34:31.469 --> 00:34:33.429
Yes, as he said, you could
make the turns slowly.

00:34:33.429 --> 00:34:35.070
It has to.

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:37.469
The knothole is only so big.

00:34:37.469 --> 00:34:43.500
But, 747's don't make
house calls.

00:34:46.730 --> 00:34:50.389
You fly by, you've got time,
you send faster ships, you

00:34:50.389 --> 00:34:54.219
explore the region, and
then, you keep going.

00:34:54.219 --> 00:34:56.790
LARRY NIVEN: And launching a
spaceship is fairly easy.

00:34:56.790 --> 00:35:01.880
You just drop it off
the edge, at around

00:35:01.880 --> 00:35:04.116
600 miles per second.

00:35:04.116 --> 00:35:06.030
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah.

00:35:06.030 --> 00:35:07.780
AUDIENCE: A pivot from plot
to business, for a

00:35:07.780 --> 00:35:08.820
moment, if you would.

00:35:08.820 --> 00:35:12.270
I'd be interested in your two
perspectives as authors on the

00:35:12.270 --> 00:35:13.390
changes in the publishing
industry,

00:35:13.390 --> 00:35:15.500
specifically related to--

00:35:15.500 --> 00:35:17.430
I don't know about the rest of
you, but I don't buy many of

00:35:17.430 --> 00:35:21.400
these in paper form anymore,
and I'd be interested in

00:35:21.400 --> 00:35:24.920
seeing how this looks from
your side of the pen.

00:35:24.920 --> 00:35:26.170
LARRY NIVEN: I carry a Kindle.

00:35:29.030 --> 00:35:30.590
BRAD TEMPLETON: Can you get
Play Store on the Kindle?

00:35:33.340 --> 00:35:34.020
GREGORY BENFORD: I don't
waste time either.

00:35:34.020 --> 00:35:39.750
LARRY NIVEN: I got my Kindle
free from Jeff Bezos, at a

00:35:39.750 --> 00:35:45.940
three-day party he threw for
around 40 of the people, and

00:35:45.940 --> 00:35:49.475
their wives and husbands,
whom he wanted to meet.

00:35:49.475 --> 00:35:49.930
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah.

00:35:49.930 --> 00:35:51.370
And the Kindle was signed.

00:35:54.860 --> 00:35:57.410
That's another thing about
collectors, is they want the

00:35:57.410 --> 00:35:59.450
print edition, you know,
information stored in the

00:35:59.450 --> 00:36:03.460
bodies of dead trees, because
you can get them signed.

00:36:03.460 --> 00:36:05.320
There are ways around that.

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:07.720
I mean David Brin and I reissued
a novel of ours,

00:36:07.720 --> 00:36:10.960
"Heart of the Comet," and we
give away a card that we have

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:13.550
signed that is that card "Heart
of the Comet." You can

00:36:13.550 --> 00:36:15.960
keep it on your file if you
want, but otherwise it's an

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:16.930
electronic edition.

00:36:16.930 --> 00:36:19.310
Although there is a
Print on Demand.

00:36:19.310 --> 00:36:21.970
But what you're talking about is
the big war that's going on

00:36:21.970 --> 00:36:23.140
in publishing.

00:36:23.140 --> 00:36:26.190
And at the moment it's really
like the opening chapters of

00:36:26.190 --> 00:36:27.030
World War II.

00:36:27.030 --> 00:36:28.400
It's all offense, no defense.

