00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:42.680
And there were several speeches

00:36:42.680 --> 00:36:45.850
at the banquet about--

00:36:45.850 --> 00:36:48.210
well they were Amazon
hate sessions.

00:36:48.210 --> 00:36:48.810
Right?

00:36:48.810 --> 00:36:52.630
I mean it was like a
scene from 1984.

00:36:52.630 --> 00:36:55.990
Everybody chants about
Big Brother.

00:36:55.990 --> 00:36:59.920
And at the same time New York
publishing was getting

00:36:59.920 --> 00:37:00.690
hollered out.

00:37:00.690 --> 00:37:03.440
You can tell it by the growing
incompetence of the staff who

00:37:03.440 --> 00:37:05.730
had been recently hired, when
they fired the executives.

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:10.860
No one seems to understand that
up ahead in the future,

00:37:10.860 --> 00:37:12.320
there's some kind
of equilibrium

00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:13.340
we're going to approach.

00:37:13.340 --> 00:37:16.950
And no one seems to be really
thinking forward about that

00:37:16.950 --> 00:37:19.220
equilibrium now.

00:37:19.220 --> 00:37:23.040
Barnes and Noble is tottering
and may collapse, the last big

00:37:23.040 --> 00:37:26.010
chain that's across
the continent.

00:37:26.010 --> 00:37:29.282
The independents are finding
niche markets, such as a Books

00:37:29.282 --> 00:37:32.740
Inc, one of my favorite
bookstores, is actually a

00:37:32.740 --> 00:37:36.670
chain about, what, seven
or eight stores.

00:37:36.670 --> 00:37:39.260
Very good store.

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:41.550
And they make a point of being
up on everything and knowing

00:37:41.550 --> 00:37:42.280
what's going on.

00:37:42.280 --> 00:37:45.390
You walk into a store, they got
the book you heard about

00:37:45.390 --> 00:37:49.510
today on NPR, or read in
the "New York Times."

00:37:49.510 --> 00:37:50.630
But how does this all work?

00:37:50.630 --> 00:37:54.390
I don't know, except the writers
are actually, I think,

00:37:54.390 --> 00:37:57.400
in many ways the biggest
beneficiaries, because we now

00:37:57.400 --> 00:37:59.240
have options.

00:37:59.240 --> 00:38:01.720
We can control our work.

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:04.600
I am reissuing my novels
selectively.

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:07.210
Although I know I could get
publishers to reissue them, I

00:38:07.210 --> 00:38:08.580
can reissue them myself.

00:38:08.580 --> 00:38:10.620
I can hire the artist.

00:38:10.620 --> 00:38:11.940
I hired a copywriter--

00:38:11.940 --> 00:38:13.190
a copy editor.

00:38:13.190 --> 00:38:15.760
I've got a promotional
editor I use.

00:38:15.760 --> 00:38:18.860
Even to revisit novels I've
written before and prune them

00:38:18.860 --> 00:38:20.740
up, and change, or readjust
the physics.

00:38:20.740 --> 00:38:22.420
I care about that
kind of thing.

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:26.290
I'm working on a novel of mine
from the from the aughts,

00:38:26.290 --> 00:38:29.220
"Cosm," which is actually
set at UCI.

00:38:29.220 --> 00:38:33.180
And it was a nice chance to
satirize other members of my

00:38:33.180 --> 00:38:34.430
department.

00:38:35.960 --> 00:38:37.620
Some of whom, luckily,
are dead.

00:38:40.390 --> 00:38:42.930
BRAD TEMPLETON: Coincedence?

00:38:42.930 --> 00:38:44.180
GREGORY BENFORD: Some say not.

00:38:47.400 --> 00:38:50.960
So we can choose our markets.

00:38:50.960 --> 00:38:54.110
We could choose to do print on
demand, or just e-Edition.

00:38:54.110 --> 00:38:57.150
I've done both.

00:38:57.150 --> 00:39:00.000
Larry's starting to reissue
his books in this way.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:02.910
The point is, the books are
going to be always available,

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:04.690
at least in digital form,
or print on demand.

00:39:04.690 --> 00:39:06.920
That's a whole new landscape
for a writer.

00:39:06.920 --> 00:39:09.660
And for this first time
in my career--

00:39:09.660 --> 00:39:11.930
our career--

00:39:11.930 --> 00:39:14.580
there's a sense of real opening
for the writers.

00:39:14.580 --> 00:39:18.170
And you may not think about it
right away, but there's the

00:39:18.170 --> 00:39:22.420
publishers, and the bookstores,
and all that, But

00:39:22.420 --> 00:39:25.920
they wouldn't have a business
without us.

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:28.470
And we're getting some control
of how we want

00:39:28.470 --> 00:39:30.260
the fields to work.

00:39:30.260 --> 00:39:31.440
And that's a good feeling.

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:35.740
LARRY NIVEN: For your sense of
proportion, my first novel, I

00:39:35.740 --> 00:39:38.816
had to settle for
4% royalties.

00:39:38.816 --> 00:39:39.230
GREGORY BENFORD: God.

00:39:39.230 --> 00:39:39.820
Really?

00:39:39.820 --> 00:39:40.650
LARRY NIVEN: Yeah.

00:39:40.650 --> 00:39:41.290
GREGORY BENFORD: "World
of Ptavvs"?

00:39:41.290 --> 00:39:42.830
LARRY NIVEN: Yeah, well
I was a novice.

00:39:42.830 --> 00:39:44.310
4% royalties.

00:39:44.310 --> 00:39:49.540
My agent later argued them into
a bigger proportion, but

00:39:49.540 --> 00:39:55.900
most people get 10%
or 8% royalties.

00:39:55.900 --> 00:40:00.330
And you get that after you've
been in the field two or three

00:40:00.330 --> 00:40:01.580
books deep.

00:40:05.590 --> 00:40:11.310
HG Wells used to get 25%,
an amazing figure.

00:40:11.310 --> 00:40:13.930
He got that, I presume,
because he put

00:40:13.930 --> 00:40:15.650
some money into it.

00:40:15.650 --> 00:40:18.740
He was part of the backing,
of the backer.

00:40:18.740 --> 00:40:20.730
I'm getting--

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:28.100
my agent is putting out my books
as the contracts lapse,

00:40:28.100 --> 00:40:33.630
and one by one they're going
into electronic print, for

00:40:33.630 --> 00:40:36.800
which I get 85%.

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:41.420
My agent keeps the 15%
she's entitled to.

00:40:41.420 --> 00:40:44.380
This is an amazing change.

00:40:44.380 --> 00:40:46.200
GREGORY BENFORD: It feels great
to do something better

00:40:46.200 --> 00:40:47.450
than HG Wells.

00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:54.790
LARRY NIVEN: Absolutely

00:40:54.790 --> 00:40:59.200
GREGORY BENFORD: So, to conclude
on that, it's a time

00:40:59.200 --> 00:41:03.370
of the greatest change since
that guy named Gutenberg.

00:41:03.370 --> 00:41:07.480
And it will mean an enormous
amount particularly to the

00:41:07.480 --> 00:41:10.680
vast majority of humanity
that has never really

00:41:10.680 --> 00:41:13.130
had access to books.

00:41:13.130 --> 00:41:17.050
I've been to India a lot, and
Africa, and believe me, these

00:41:17.050 --> 00:41:20.030
are people who are starved for
information, and have been so

00:41:20.030 --> 00:41:22.690
for thousands of years.

00:41:22.690 --> 00:41:24.170
Can you imagine the civilization
that was

00:41:24.170 --> 00:41:26.500
information starved forever?

00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:27.950
Well read the history books.

00:41:27.950 --> 00:41:30.350
That's most of human history.

00:41:30.350 --> 00:41:32.850
This is really going
to alter humanity.

00:41:32.850 --> 00:41:36.840
And I, with my biases, think,
look, I come from a small town

00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:38.720
in southern Alabama.

00:41:38.720 --> 00:41:39.630
Information starved?

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:40.940
I know what we're
talking about.

00:41:40.940 --> 00:41:42.180
I went to-- my brother and I--

00:41:42.180 --> 00:41:43.110
I'm an identical twin--

00:41:43.110 --> 00:41:47.210
went to a one room schoolhouse
when we were growing up, in a

00:41:47.210 --> 00:41:49.180
farm community.

00:41:49.180 --> 00:41:51.200
It changes your view
of the world.

00:41:53.940 --> 00:41:56.230
LARRY NIVEN: That it does.

00:41:56.230 --> 00:42:00.220
AUDIENCE: So our species used
to build things, that-- you

00:42:00.220 --> 00:42:03.460
know we have ruins from
millennia ago, and now you're

00:42:03.460 --> 00:42:07.590
in front of a room full of
people who routinely get woken

00:42:07.590 --> 00:42:09.380
up in the middle of the
night because our

00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:11.520
system needs our help.

00:42:11.520 --> 00:42:16.230
So I'm wondering if you see sort
of a broad societal trend

00:42:16.230 --> 00:42:21.450
towards building smarter
objects that need more

00:42:21.450 --> 00:42:23.190
maintenance.

00:42:23.190 --> 00:42:25.970
LARRY NIVEN: Smarter objects
that need more maintenance?

00:42:25.970 --> 00:42:27.450
Obama would support that.

00:42:31.480 --> 00:42:34.000
Jobs.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:34.970
GREGORY BENFORD: You
mean Steve, or--

00:42:34.970 --> 00:42:36.220
LARRY NIVEN: No, I mean jobs.

00:42:40.120 --> 00:42:42.600
GREGORY BENFORD: That is an
interesting way to look at it.

00:42:42.600 --> 00:42:45.580
But the reason is, of course,
that builds a

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:47.860
society of smart people.

00:42:47.860 --> 00:42:50.270
I mean people who can manage
a complex system.

00:42:50.270 --> 00:42:54.680
If you're building the pyramids,
a Big Dumb Object,

00:42:54.680 --> 00:42:56.030
you don't need literate
people.

00:42:58.930 --> 00:43:05.190
So it's easy to be impressed
by gargantuan things.

00:43:05.190 --> 00:43:09.540
But Gargantuan Smart Things is
qualitatively different.

00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:12.440
I wrote a whole book, which in
fact I'm going to bring back

00:43:12.440 --> 00:43:15.627
in print within a year or so,
called "Deep Time." The

00:43:15.627 --> 00:43:18.190
subtitle was "How Humanity
Communicates Across

00:43:18.190 --> 00:43:21.410
Millennia." It's nonfiction
about my experience of trying

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:24.300
to design long-term messages
in various places, like the

00:43:24.300 --> 00:43:26.700
nuclear waste facility in New
Mexico, and the Cassini

00:43:26.700 --> 00:43:27.840
mission to Saturn.

00:43:27.840 --> 00:43:30.500
And one of the things I learned,
to my astonishment,

00:43:30.500 --> 00:43:34.360
is that there were many museums,
and art galleries,

00:43:34.360 --> 00:43:37.080
and libraries in the
ancient world.

00:43:37.080 --> 00:43:41.420
Guess how many survived the
collapse of the Roman Empire,

00:43:41.420 --> 00:43:42.960
or other empires?

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:45.340
Zero.

00:43:45.340 --> 00:43:47.140
Parts of them were left over.

00:43:47.140 --> 00:43:50.120
None of the institutions
survived.

00:43:50.120 --> 00:43:54.511
So, if you really want a
long-term message, in the

00:43:54.511 --> 00:43:58.940
ancient past anyway, you should
invest in granite.

00:43:58.940 --> 00:44:01.340
Carve it deep and leave
it in a desert.

00:44:01.340 --> 00:44:02.700
AUDIENCE: I'm a big
"Ringworld" fan.

00:44:02.700 --> 00:44:07.430
And recently computer graphics
imaging has, I think, made it

00:44:07.430 --> 00:44:09.160
possible to actually make
movies out of this.

00:44:09.160 --> 00:44:12.330
Not that it might fit in two
or three hours, but I just

00:44:12.330 --> 00:44:14.780
wondered what you thought
of those kinds of ideas.

00:44:14.780 --> 00:44:19.080
And, I think, in general the
idea of books are wonderful

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:21.700
because you don't need any
computer graphics imaging.

00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:23.050
You can think of it
in your mind.

00:44:23.050 --> 00:44:25.350
But now we have the technology
to do all these kinds of

00:44:25.350 --> 00:44:30.340
movies, and are we making
readers dumber by making these

00:44:30.340 --> 00:44:32.470
movies with big explosions?

00:44:32.470 --> 00:44:36.000
LARRY NIVEN: Are we making
readers dumber by showing so

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.096
much in a movie?

00:44:38.096 --> 00:44:39.640
GREGORY BENFORD: Well we're
making moviegoers dumber.

00:44:42.550 --> 00:44:45.850
But tell them about the
"Ringworld" movie.

00:44:45.850 --> 00:44:50.110
LARRY NIVEN: The "Ringworld"
movie has suffered over the

00:44:50.110 --> 00:44:53.690
decades because I signed some
papers I shouldn't have early

00:44:53.690 --> 00:44:54.550
in my career.

00:44:54.550 --> 00:45:02.320
But we renegotiated a contract
a couple years ago and now

00:45:02.320 --> 00:45:07.890
that the guy who has the right
to has shopped it to MGM.

00:45:07.890 --> 00:45:09.440
That's all I know.

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:11.720
The movie is at MGM.

00:45:11.720 --> 00:45:13.660
And if [? Mandel ?]

00:45:13.660 --> 00:45:16.820
fails to come through
with it, I get a

00:45:16.820 --> 00:45:18.630
chance to make a movie.

00:45:18.630 --> 00:45:20.870
But that won't happen
for a little while.

00:45:20.870 --> 00:45:22.280
GREGORY BENFORD: But everything
you say about

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:25.700
special effects is quite so.

00:45:25.700 --> 00:45:27.470
AUDIENCE: You don't really
need actors anymore.

00:45:27.470 --> 00:45:29.340
GREGORY BENFORD: No, and you
don't even need a big budget.

00:45:29.340 --> 00:45:34.240
Remember the movie "Moon" made
by the son of a famous rock

00:45:34.240 --> 00:45:38.960
star for, what was
it, a million?

00:45:38.960 --> 00:45:44.370
It was some small sum, and it
made tens of millions, because

00:45:44.370 --> 00:45:45.740
there was a good script.

00:45:45.740 --> 00:45:47.700
And it was a smart script.

00:45:47.700 --> 00:45:51.080
And the special effects
were cheap.

00:45:51.080 --> 00:45:54.260
LARRY NIVEN: I'm remembering
"Tom Corbett, Space Cadet."

00:45:54.260 --> 00:45:56.240
when you had to imagine
most of what you were

00:45:56.240 --> 00:45:57.810
supposed to be seeing.

00:45:57.810 --> 00:45:58.930
GREGORY BENFORD: Hell,
you had to imagine

00:45:58.930 --> 00:46:00.990
what you were seeing.

00:46:00.990 --> 00:46:03.620
I mean, rocket ships,
in which the exhaust

00:46:03.620 --> 00:46:07.050
rises, as it goes across.

00:46:07.050 --> 00:46:08.750
Yeah, well.

00:46:08.750 --> 00:46:10.580
I mean, it never occurred to
them, apparently, to turn the

00:46:10.580 --> 00:46:13.420
camera sideways and just have
a rocket ship come down like

00:46:13.420 --> 00:46:17.910
this, so the exhaust would
appear to be going away from

00:46:17.910 --> 00:46:18.550
the rocket.

00:46:18.550 --> 00:46:21.420
LARRY NIVEN: Do you know how
they got freefall in "2001: A

00:46:21.420 --> 00:46:23.880
Space Odyssey"?

00:46:23.880 --> 00:46:26.980
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah they
spun the giant hoop.

00:46:26.980 --> 00:46:30.460
LARRY NIVEN: They put the
astronaut on a line, and then

00:46:30.460 --> 00:46:33.950
shot him from underneath so
that the line didn't show.

00:46:33.950 --> 00:46:34.720
Now he's in freefall.

00:46:34.720 --> 00:46:37.090
GREGORY BENFORD: Right.

00:46:37.090 --> 00:46:40.300
And it was remarkably
convincing.

00:46:40.300 --> 00:46:41.550
It really was.

00:46:43.190 --> 00:46:46.790
Arthur Clarke gave me a
photograph of him walking

00:46:46.790 --> 00:46:52.070
through that rotating drum that
they use for the interior

00:46:52.070 --> 00:46:53.120
of the spaceship.

00:46:53.120 --> 00:46:55.240
Do you know the famous
establishing shot where the

00:46:55.240 --> 00:46:57.020
guy appears to run
over the ceiling?

00:46:57.020 --> 00:46:58.570
And he did the same thing.

00:46:58.570 --> 00:47:00.370
He said there's a film of him
doing the same thing.

00:47:00.370 --> 00:47:01.400
But I haven't seen it.

00:47:01.400 --> 00:47:07.520
But it was funny to see him in
this futuristic context, which

00:47:07.520 --> 00:47:11.780
now lies in the past, "2001."

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:13.740
AUDIENCE: I like the way they
did the special effects for

00:47:13.740 --> 00:47:17.660
"Apollo 13" to get
the zero gravity.

00:47:17.660 --> 00:47:18.970
Back to something
you just said.

00:47:18.970 --> 00:47:21.410
So on the one hand, we have
electronic books, which means

00:47:21.410 --> 00:47:23.480
you can reissue things, you can
publish things, you make

00:47:23.480 --> 00:47:26.870
more money with it, which I
think is wonderful by the way.

00:47:26.870 --> 00:47:29.000
The downside is, something that
you just said, if you

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:30.910
want it to last, put
it in granite.

00:47:30.910 --> 00:47:33.570
One of the reasons I don't buy
electronic books is I don't

00:47:33.570 --> 00:47:35.900
want Amazon deciding that, for
some reason, I didn't buy

00:47:35.900 --> 00:47:37.860
their electronic book, after
I've already got it.

00:47:37.860 --> 00:47:38.940
You know, I want to keep it.

00:47:38.940 --> 00:47:41.480
I want to have my own backup,
and my own copies.

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:42.740
GREGORY BENFORD:
Well, buy both.

00:47:42.740 --> 00:47:48.350
AUDIENCE: Well, it
it's in print.

00:47:48.350 --> 00:47:50.310
But again, if it's in print,
or if it's only

00:47:50.310 --> 00:47:51.210
in electronic form.

00:47:51.210 --> 00:47:53.490
I can go to the used bookstore,
and look forever,

00:47:53.490 --> 00:47:55.010
and maybe find it,
and maybe not.

00:47:55.010 --> 00:47:59.160
Where do you stand on that sort
of DRM restrictions--

00:47:59.160 --> 00:48:01.395
you know, high price, low price,
and mass distribution--

00:48:01.395 --> 00:48:02.645
kind of thing?

00:48:05.060 --> 00:48:07.780
LARRY NIVEN: I like
cheaper books.

00:48:07.780 --> 00:48:09.740
AUDIENCE: Yeah, me too.

00:48:09.740 --> 00:48:12.380
GREGORY BENFORD: Except ours.

00:48:12.380 --> 00:48:14.606
AUDIENCE: If you keep it up,
everybody buys them, right?

00:48:14.606 --> 00:48:17.090
So, it's kind of a tradeoff.

00:48:17.090 --> 00:48:18.630
LARRY NIVEN: I want
my ideas spread.

00:48:18.630 --> 00:48:20.780
I don't even mind pirates
very much.

00:48:20.780 --> 00:48:22.400
I mind them some.

00:48:22.400 --> 00:48:24.130
GREGORY BENFORD: True.

00:48:24.130 --> 00:48:25.470
What you bring up is
a serious issue.

00:48:25.470 --> 00:48:28.430
First, I'm against DRM.

00:48:28.430 --> 00:48:30.980
Second, if you really want to
keep your electronic books

00:48:30.980 --> 00:48:34.060
safe and preserved forever,
well you could put them in

00:48:34.060 --> 00:48:37.420
orbit where I don't think
they can reach them.

00:48:37.420 --> 00:48:40.320
But it's always good
to have a backup.

00:48:40.320 --> 00:48:42.250
I mean, that's what I tell
people when they say, what is

00:48:42.250 --> 00:48:43.700
it like to be an
identical twin.

00:48:43.700 --> 00:48:47.960
I say, have a backup.

00:48:47.960 --> 00:48:53.820
So I too like physical books.

00:48:53.820 --> 00:48:55.940
And I have a few electronic
books but I don't

00:48:55.940 --> 00:48:57.300
mostly read that way.

00:48:59.940 --> 00:49:03.030
But they're crowding me
out of my houses,

00:49:03.030 --> 00:49:04.744
so there's the downside.

00:49:04.744 --> 00:49:06.400
LARRY NIVEN: Me too.

00:49:06.400 --> 00:49:09.990
If you can't bear to throw away
a book, you're in trouble

00:49:09.990 --> 00:49:11.630
eventually.

00:49:11.630 --> 00:49:13.190
They pile up.

00:49:13.190 --> 00:49:15.314
GREGORY BENFORD: And
thank you for it.

00:49:15.314 --> 00:49:18.190
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:18.190 --> 00:49:19.020
GREGORY BENFORD: Oh great.

00:49:19.020 --> 00:49:20.240
BRAD TEMPLETON: Oh, there
are books I've

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:23.470
wanted to throw away.

00:49:23.470 --> 00:49:25.450
GREGORY BENFORD: Well, you know,
as a conservationist,

00:49:25.450 --> 00:49:26.700
you could burn them for heat.

00:49:29.460 --> 00:49:32.820
Which further has a benefit that
other people will not be

00:49:32.820 --> 00:49:34.570
troubled by reading.

00:49:34.570 --> 00:49:36.340
BRAD TEMPLETON: So, you've
touched on this a little bit,

00:49:36.340 --> 00:49:39.180
but I was wondering if you might
want to talk a little

00:49:39.180 --> 00:49:40.320
bit more about collaboration.

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:43.080
I mean, I think, Larry, you're
becoming known as a great

00:49:43.080 --> 00:49:44.190
collaborator.

00:49:44.190 --> 00:49:46.258
Once, when I was angry at Jerry
Pournelle, I told him,

00:49:46.258 --> 00:49:48.040
you know Jerry, you write really
good books when you

00:49:48.040 --> 00:49:50.330
work with Larry.

00:49:50.330 --> 00:49:51.417
So.

00:49:51.417 --> 00:49:52.550
GREGORY BENFORD: And he said?

00:49:52.550 --> 00:49:55.910
LARRY NIVEN: I think he
was flattered, myself.

00:49:55.910 --> 00:49:58.605
I write really good books
when I write with Jerry.

00:49:58.605 --> 00:49:59.490
BRAD TEMPLETON: No,
you do actually.

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:01.520
I think the two of you together
do stuff that you

00:50:01.520 --> 00:50:02.680
don't do on your own.

00:50:02.680 --> 00:50:05.810
So tell me what is about the
collaborative process that

00:50:05.810 --> 00:50:08.600
makes that happen.

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:11.050
LARRY NIVEN: You learn each
other's strengths.

00:50:11.050 --> 00:50:14.320
Jerry's, for instance, are with
military and politics.

00:50:14.320 --> 00:50:19.290
Mine are with aliens, and
characters who go crazy.

00:50:19.290 --> 00:50:20.690
GREGORY BENFORD: Yeah,
that's true.

00:50:20.690 --> 00:50:21.570
Crazy characters.

00:50:21.570 --> 00:50:22.110
LARRY NIVEN: Yeah.

00:50:22.110 --> 00:50:26.330
When a heroic character is
wading his way through a sea

00:50:26.330 --> 00:50:31.690
of troubles, fighting his way
toward a goal, that's Jerry.

00:50:31.690 --> 00:50:34.210
The character goes
nuts, that's me.

00:50:37.280 --> 00:50:39.180
GREGORY BENFORD: It says so
much about your lives.

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:42.880
LARRY NIVEN: Collaborations
are more fun, and more

00:50:42.880 --> 00:50:46.800
friendly, than sitting at your
typewriter all alone writing.

00:50:46.800 --> 00:50:49.390
Of course, as a collaborator
you're going to do a lot of

00:50:49.390 --> 00:50:54.010
that anyway, because you don't
live together in the same

00:50:54.010 --> 00:50:55.260
house unless you're
man and wife.

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:01.820
Jerry and I live about 25
minutes away from each other.

00:51:05.400 --> 00:51:09.550
Greg lives an hour and a
half away, maybe two.

00:51:12.400 --> 00:51:15.470
But we've got the internet.

00:51:15.470 --> 00:51:18.310
When we didn't have the
internet, Jerry lived a little

00:51:18.310 --> 00:51:22.970
closer and it was easier, but
we still had to carry texts

00:51:22.970 --> 00:51:24.250
back and forth.

00:51:24.250 --> 00:51:25.550
BRAD TEMPLETON: What, are you
saying as soon as he got the

00:51:25.550 --> 00:51:29.510
internet, he moved further
away from you?

00:51:29.510 --> 00:51:30.840
LARRY NIVEN: You got the
right idea, but I

00:51:30.840 --> 00:51:32.665
was the one who moved.

00:51:32.665 --> 00:51:33.120
GREGORY BENFORD: Right.

00:51:33.120 --> 00:51:34.090
To a bigger house.

00:51:34.090 --> 00:51:34.950
Bigger still.

00:51:34.950 --> 00:51:36.510
LARRY NIVEN: Yeah.

00:51:36.510 --> 00:51:37.650
The books were piling up.

00:51:37.650 --> 00:51:41.380
We had to move to
a bigger house.

00:51:41.380 --> 00:51:43.750
GREGORY BENFORD: You're
quite right.

00:51:43.750 --> 00:51:45.820
We have different strengths.

00:51:45.820 --> 00:51:49.890
You know, physicist He's
an alien tech--

00:51:49.890 --> 00:51:51.490
He's an alien.

00:51:51.490 --> 00:51:55.500
LARRY NIVEN: Greg has got the
electromagnetic fields that I

00:51:55.500 --> 00:51:59.410
don't know very much about it.

00:51:59.410 --> 00:52:01.870
GREGORY BENFORD: But it's also
true that writing is a lonely

00:52:01.870 --> 00:52:06.520
business, and you can
advance your ideas

00:52:06.520 --> 00:52:08.320
faster by speaking them.

00:52:08.320 --> 00:52:09.980
We all know that.

00:52:09.980 --> 00:52:14.390
And kicking ideas back and forth
generates new ideas at a

00:52:14.390 --> 00:52:18.055
much, much faster rate than
sitting there staring at a a

00:52:18.055 --> 00:52:19.140
cathode ray tube.

00:52:19.140 --> 00:52:21.490
Or a stream of some kind.

00:52:21.490 --> 00:52:24.070
It's just one of the strengths
of human beings.

00:52:24.070 --> 00:52:25.950
We are a collaborative
species.

00:52:25.950 --> 00:52:26.260
Right?

00:52:26.260 --> 00:52:28.220
That's why we talk so much.

00:52:28.220 --> 00:52:33.012
LARRY NIVEN: I do not have the
patience to be a scientist.

00:52:33.012 --> 00:52:34.650
I knew that fairly early.

00:52:37.270 --> 00:52:40.760
GREGORY BENFORD: And there's
a deeper thing here.

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:44.430
Modern science fiction, by the
way, which invented fandom--

00:52:44.430 --> 00:52:48.320
the word and the thing itself,
and fanzines, and all that--

00:52:48.320 --> 00:52:50.920
came out of the scientific,
technical culture.

00:52:50.920 --> 00:52:54.880
It has always been marked by a
high degree of collaboration.

00:52:54.880 --> 00:52:56.380
And that is true in
the scientific

00:52:56.380 --> 00:52:57.840
and engineering culture.

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:00.110
This is not true in the
literary culture.

00:53:00.110 --> 00:53:02.310
Collaborations are rare.

00:53:02.310 --> 00:53:04.080
It's because they come
out of an older,

00:53:04.080 --> 00:53:05.670
and different culture.

00:53:05.670 --> 00:53:08.380
Scientists inherently
collaborate.

00:53:08.380 --> 00:53:10.710
By far, the majority of all
scientific papers are

00:53:10.710 --> 00:53:12.260
collaborations.

00:53:12.260 --> 00:53:16.150
A high fraction of SF work
is collaboration.

00:53:16.150 --> 00:53:18.920
A minority, but far higher
than in other fields.

00:53:18.920 --> 00:53:21.470
Even in mysteries, there are
very few collaborations.

00:53:21.470 --> 00:53:23.080
Westerns, romance novels--

00:53:23.080 --> 00:53:25.340
they're almost all individual
writers.

00:53:25.340 --> 00:53:26.920
Not so, in science fiction.

00:53:26.920 --> 00:53:30.670
And so it underlies the fact
that science fiction is a

00:53:30.670 --> 00:53:33.070
cultural expression
of the dominant

00:53:33.070 --> 00:53:34.860
force in modern times--

00:53:34.860 --> 00:53:36.470
science and technology.

00:53:36.470 --> 00:53:40.370
Try to imagine the last two
centuries without science and

00:53:40.370 --> 00:53:42.990
technology, and its
rate of change.

00:53:42.990 --> 00:53:45.620
Actually try to imagine the last
two centuries without the

00:53:45.620 --> 00:53:47.640
United States of America, but
that's another discussion.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:54.370
So you ought to realize this
is actually part of a very

00:53:54.370 --> 00:53:58.760
much larger phenomena that
is taking over the world.

00:53:58.760 --> 00:54:02.760
We have many competitors
in Asia, and so forth.

00:54:02.760 --> 00:54:05.970
They're copying our methods.

00:54:05.970 --> 00:54:07.880
Some years ago, at the World
Science Fiction Convention in

00:54:07.880 --> 00:54:11.810
Tokyo, I spoke to the team of
six editors from the Chinese

00:54:11.810 --> 00:54:13.410
science fiction magazine.

00:54:13.410 --> 00:54:15.470
We've never had a science
fiction magazine, and they had

00:54:15.470 --> 00:54:16.540
six editors.

00:54:16.540 --> 00:54:17.210
It's a monthly.

00:54:17.210 --> 00:54:20.650
It has circulation of about a
third to a half a million

00:54:20.650 --> 00:54:25.550
copies, whereas "Analog" sells
about 35,000 a month.

00:54:25.550 --> 00:54:28.860
And the Chinese government
supports this magazine--

00:54:28.860 --> 00:54:32.700
subsidizes it-- because they
want to invert the process.

00:54:32.700 --> 00:54:36.960
You see, the first science
fiction magazine was "Amazing

00:54:36.960 --> 00:54:39.970
Stories" published by a group
of radio magazines.

00:54:39.970 --> 00:54:42.220
And it was the anomaly
inside there.

00:54:42.220 --> 00:54:45.100
And it's the only one that
anyone remembers now.

00:54:45.100 --> 00:54:48.910
The Chinese want to draw their
own people into the culture of

00:54:48.910 --> 00:54:52.410
science and technology and the
habits of mind, by using

00:54:52.410 --> 00:54:53.800
science fiction.

00:54:53.800 --> 00:54:55.880
They're inverting--

00:54:55.880 --> 00:54:56.970
reverse engineering--

00:54:56.970 --> 00:54:58.080
what we did naturally and

00:54:58.080 --> 00:55:00.040
spontaneously in the 20th century.

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:02.040
So this has been an important
phenomena

00:55:02.040 --> 00:55:03.480
going around the world.

00:55:03.480 --> 00:55:05.070
And it's the reason there
are now science fiction

00:55:05.070 --> 00:55:07.760
conventions in India, and other

00:55:07.760 --> 00:55:09.790
seemingly unlikely places.

00:55:09.790 --> 00:55:11.820
Africa, even.

00:55:11.820 --> 00:55:15.200
And it's part of the shaping of
human culture that is being

00:55:15.200 --> 00:55:20.140
done by you, the technological
elite.

00:55:24.370 --> 00:55:26.710
BRAD TEMPLETON: So I
think we're running

00:55:26.710 --> 00:55:28.600
close to the end.

00:55:28.600 --> 00:55:30.830
I'll ask one last question,
actually, because you two are

00:55:30.830 --> 00:55:34.230
both well-known for being
specialists in hard science

00:55:34.230 --> 00:55:37.360
fiction, by which I like to call
realistic science fiction

00:55:37.360 --> 00:55:38.810
that actually follows
the physics.

00:55:38.810 --> 00:55:41.230
And now it's not just necessary
to follow physics.

00:55:41.230 --> 00:55:43.850
I often say romance novels have
excellent physics, and

00:55:43.850 --> 00:55:48.410
they barely violate
those laws.

00:55:48.410 --> 00:55:50.080
They may violate the laws
of chemistry, but

00:55:50.080 --> 00:55:51.690
not the laws of physics.

00:55:51.690 --> 00:55:52.770
GREGORY BENFORD:
And of biology.

00:55:52.770 --> 00:55:54.670
BRAD TEMPLETON: But what is it
that you feel is the great

00:55:54.670 --> 00:55:55.770
virtue of hard science
fiction?

00:55:55.770 --> 00:55:57.680
What is it that makes-- when you
sit down to write, why do

00:55:57.680 --> 00:56:01.250
you feel that that's what
you must write?

00:56:01.250 --> 00:56:03.660
LARRY NIVEN: I'm not a fanatic
on the subject.

00:56:03.660 --> 00:56:05.510
I have written science
fiction.

00:56:05.510 --> 00:56:07.290
I've written fantasy.

00:56:07.290 --> 00:56:10.150
I have written detective
fiction.

00:56:10.150 --> 00:56:13.400
When I get up the nerve, I
write detective science

00:56:13.400 --> 00:56:20.560
fiction, and I've got to tell
you, it's the hardest work.

00:56:20.560 --> 00:56:23.380
I generally write science
fiction because that's where

00:56:23.380 --> 00:56:25.380
my ideas come from.

00:56:25.380 --> 00:56:31.330
I've got no contempt for every
other field of fiction.

00:56:31.330 --> 00:56:33.220
They will all teach you
to read, and reading

00:56:33.220 --> 00:56:34.470
teaches you to think.

00:56:38.880 --> 00:56:43.380
There was a phenomenon
called Laser Books.

00:56:43.380 --> 00:56:49.040
Laser Books was going to be
science fiction, as produced

00:56:49.040 --> 00:56:53.320
by a house that produced
mostly romance--

00:56:53.320 --> 00:56:55.580
well, all romance novels.

00:56:55.580 --> 00:56:58.190
They were going to branch out,
going to be science fiction,

00:56:58.190 --> 00:57:01.630
going to be the label that
sells, rather than the

00:57:01.630 --> 00:57:02.880
author's name.

00:57:04.928 --> 00:57:08.400
This, as far as I was concerned,
was a great way to

00:57:08.400 --> 00:57:12.240
train readers to read, and
eventually they would grow up

00:57:12.240 --> 00:57:15.310
and read my stuff.

00:57:15.310 --> 00:57:19.570
As it turned out, the name
was what sold anyway.

00:57:19.570 --> 00:57:23.220
And I do mean the name
of the author.

00:57:23.220 --> 00:57:28.980
Robert Gleason, my favorite
editor, told me that he was--

00:57:28.980 --> 00:57:32.830
he tends to travel among the
people who transport the books

00:57:32.830 --> 00:57:36.290
to the stores, the
distributors.

00:57:36.290 --> 00:57:43.420
He told me he was at a bar where
they were gathered, and

00:57:43.420 --> 00:57:47.670
from the next table he hears,
there's only one Laser Book

00:57:47.670 --> 00:57:53.550
that sells at all well, and
it's by one author.

00:57:53.550 --> 00:57:55.086
And his name [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:59.060 --> 00:58:03.350
It turned out to be Jerry
Pournelle's Laser books were

00:58:03.350 --> 00:58:07.360
the only ones who sold
well, among Laser.

00:58:07.360 --> 00:58:10.900
And Laser bowed out gracefully,
returned all

00:58:10.900 --> 00:58:18.530
rights, got out of the field,
and it was one of those happy

00:58:18.530 --> 00:58:23.660
stories, as far as people who
think that the author's name

00:58:23.660 --> 00:58:27.290
ought to be what sells
books best.

00:58:27.290 --> 00:58:28.540
BRAD TEMPLETON: All right, well,
on that note I'd like to

00:58:28.540 --> 00:58:31.280
thank our two guests for a
fabulous presentation.

00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:38.247
[APPLAUSE]

